Q: Is there a way to get a multiline TextField to size to fit so I can put a button directly next to it? A: <p>This question was initially closed because it was deemed a duplicate of <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/q/62309537/20386264">SwiftUI TextField takes max width</a>. However, that question is about a single-line <code>TextField</code> and the solution was to apply the modifier <code>.fixedSize()</code>. <strong>This modifier does not work for a multiline text field</strong> and causes the field to collapse to zero width.</p>
<p>A similar issue was also addressed in the question <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/q/79280568/20386264">How to dynamically adjust the width of a TextField to its content?</a> The solution provided there was to use a <code>Text</code> item with fixed size in the background and to apply its width to the text field in the foreground. This approach <strong>also does not work for a multiline text field</strong>, because applying <code>.fixedSize()</code> to <code>Text</code> causes it to stay on one line.</p>
<hr />
<p>To solve the multiline case, we need a way to find the footprint of the text such that (a) the width is kept to the minimum necessary but (b) the text is still able to wrap to multiple lines when it is long.</p>
<p>A <code>Text</code> field with <code>.fixedSize(horizontal: false, vertical: true)</code> works this way. So a possible solution is to use this to get the footprint of the text, then show the <code>TextField</code> as an overlay.</p>
<p>Here is an adaption of the code in the question to show it working:</p>
<pre class="lang-swift prettyprint-override"><code>struct ContentView: View {
    @State private var textFieldUserInput = &quot;&quot;

    var body: some View {
        HStack(alignment: .firstTextBaseline) {
            Text(textFieldUserInput.isEmpty ? &quot;Prompt&quot; : textFieldUserInput)
                .fixedSize(horizontal: false, vertical: true)
                .hidden()
                .overlay(alignment: .topLeading) {
                    TextField(&quot;Prompt&quot;, text: $textFieldUserInput, axis: .vertical)
                        .textFieldStyle(.plain)
                }
            Button(&quot;X&quot;) {}
                .buttonStyle(.borderedProminent)
        }
        .padding()
        .frame(maxWidth: .infinity, minHeight: 300, alignment: .topLeading)
    }
}
</code></pre>
<p><img src="https://i.sstatic.net/Odf6Zg18.gif" alt="Animation" /></p>
<hr />
<p>Ps. I was expecting that the text shown in the <code>TextField</code> might jump around with every character entered, because the size of the footprint changes as a <em>reaction</em> to the input. This is in fact the case when running on macOS, see <a href="https://stackoverflow.com/q/79615687/20386264">TextField with .fixedSize() is jumping when edited</a>. On iOS it doesn't seem to be a problem. However, if you do encounter this kind of issue, you could try adding padding to the <code>Text</code>, so that the <code>TextField</code> in the overlay has enough space for another character to be entered without needing to wrap. For example, try adding <code>.padding(.horizontal, 2)</code> to the <code>Text</code> footprint, just before the <code>.overlay</code>.</p>

Q: Creating nested dataclass objects in Python A: <p>You can add your own <code>__init__</code> method:</p>
<pre class="lang-py prettyprint-override"><code>from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import Mapping

@dataclass
class One:
    f_one: int
    f_two: str

@dataclass
class Two:
    f_three: str
    f_four: One
    def __init__(self, f_three: str, f_four: Mapping):
        self.f_three = f_three
        self.f_four = One(**f_four)

data = {'f_three': 'three', 'f_four': {'f_one': 1, 'f_two': 'two'}}
print(Two(**data))
</code></pre>
<p>The <code>@dataclass</code> decorator automatically adds multiple methods to the class for you. But you can still manually write those you want to customize.</p>

Q: Group summary notification not canceled when last containing notification is canceled A: <p>Kotlin and improved code based on @MateuszKaflowski answer and @SergeyStasishin comment.</p>
<p>Advantages:</p>
<ol>
<li>Using <code>NotificationManagerCompat</code> for avoid self SDK version check</li>
<li>Add notification tag usage</li>
<li>Exclude <code>summaryId</code> input parameter for group notification cancel</li>
</ol>
<pre class="lang-kotlin prettyprint-override"><code>fun cancelNotification(context: Context, tag: String?, id: Int) {
    with(NotificationManagerCompat.from(context)) {
        val groupKey = activeNotifications.find { it.tag == tag &amp;&amp; it.id == id }?.groupKey
        cancel(tag, id)
        groupKey ?: return
        with(activeNotifications.filter { it.groupKey == groupKey }) {
            firstOrNull()?.let { cancel(it.tag, it.id) }
        }
    }
}
</code></pre>
